Consider an object moving with a changing acceleration.<br><ul><li>Let&nbsp;\(v\)&nbsp;represent the velocity at time&nbsp;\(t\)</li><li>Let&nbsp;\(v+\delta v\)&nbsp;represent the velocity a short time later at&nbsp;\(t+\delta t\)</li></ul><ol><li>Because&nbsp;\(\delta v\)&nbsp;is small compared to&nbsp;\(v\), the&nbsp;<b>displacement</b>&nbsp;in a short time interval&nbsp;\(\delta t\)&nbsp;is&nbsp;\(\delta s=v\delta t\)</li><li>Consider the&nbsp;<b>whole area</b>&nbsp;under the line in strips of similar width, the&nbsp;<b>total displacement</b>&nbsp;from the start to time&nbsp;\(t\)&nbsp;is represented by the sum of the area of every strip.</li></ol><div>So it gives the displacement.<br></div>